<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister Blames Extremists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2101032094 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2101032094 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Concerning the disturbances that have been taking 
place in various educational institutions throughout the 
country, Interior Relations Minister Carlos Delgado Chapellin 
reiterated that these incidents are being caused by small groups 
of troublemakers. He added that these groups include suspected 
extremists who are being investigated. 
  [Begin recording] [Chapellin] I believe that this would seem 
to be a political tactic that will lead nowhere. Some high 
school students are being manipulated. They are students who 
are being misled [words indistinct] by people who have nothing 
to do with the educational sector. These disturbances have no 
popular support, and the best thing the students can do is to go 
home and study and allow the elected president to be sworn-in 
peacefully. 
  [Reporter] Mr. Minister, by whom are they being manipulated? 
  [Chapellin] Manipulated by forces associated with the 
so-called extremists. We are currently investigating several 
extremists. There might be some surprises in terms of who is 
manipulating these squalid protest marches. Do not blow these 
disturbances out of proportion because they are worthless. 
  [Reporter] Will the authorities ever uncover who... 
  [Chapellin, interrupting] Of course we will. Just yesterday 
[words indistinct] four masked men. The university authorities 
were the first to [word indistinct]. Let us give... 
  [Reporter, interrupting] Yes, but the uncertainty caused by 
these same four people... 
  [Chapellin] Well, we will have to arrest those four people, 
even if they decide to hide on university grounds. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

