<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   President-Elect Caldera Meets With Reform Committee Members </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2101210594 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2101210594 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ligia Moreno; from "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President-elect Rafael Caldera has met with members 
of the Presidential Committee to Reform the State [Copre] to 
study constitutional reforms. Copre members have handed to the 
president-elect a document containing the main reforms, which, 
according to this group, should be implemented during the next 
constitutional term. Three salient points are highlighted: 
profound reforms of the constitution and public administration, 
and decentralization. 
  Among the major changes are a reorganization of the Congress 
of the republic, a review of the Supreme Electoral Council, and 
the possible creation of a post that already exists in most 
European countries; that is, that of prime minister. 
  [Begin Copre President Trino Marquez, as identified by 
caption, recording, in progress] ...agrees with this proposal. 
President Caldera told us about the need to reform the 
Constitution to allow the creation of the post of prime 
minister, because certain regulations restrict the relationship 
between the Executive Branch and other branches; thus, a 
constitutional reform is needed. This was one of his proposals. 
We must firmly promote a comprehensive reform of the 
Constitution. [end recording] 
  At any rate, the president of the Republic cannot create a 
new ministry. As a last resort he could create a ministry 
without portfolio, however, solely to give him advice. 

</TEXT>

