<H3> <TI>   Robaina Continues African Tour in Namibia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Three-Year Trade Agreement Signed </H4>
<F P=102> FL2101181994 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 1403 GMT 
21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2101181994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The governments of Cuba and Namibia today in 
Windhoek signed an important commercial agreement granting each 
other favored-nation treatment. The three-year agreement was 
signed by Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina and Namibian 
Trade and Industry Minister Hidipo Hamutenya. The agreement 
states that the signing countries will make all payments in 
freely convertible currency and in accordance with the laws of 
the two countries. Robaina and Hamutenya agreed that the 
bilateral agreement will open the way for identifying other 
areas of cooperation. 
  The Cuban foreign minister today concludes his three-day 
official visit to Namibia, the last leg of his two-week tour of 
Africa, during which he visited Ghana, Angola, Zimbabwe, and 
Zambia. Before leaving Namibia, Foreign Minister Robaina will 
meet with Namibian President Sam Nujoma. 

</TEXT>

