<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Camaguey Bus Workers Benefit From Profit-Sharing Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1901024894 </F>
<F P=103> FL1901024894 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 
at 0000 GMT on 19 January features a report in three parts by 
correspondent Diosdado Maso from Camaguey City. Maso reports 
that the Urban Buses Enterprise has established a new pilot 
system on three routes which consists of a profit- sharing 
scheme among the inspector, mechanic, driver, and electrician of 
each bus, where a percentage of the profits are divided among 
them at the end of each shift. 
  Maso interviews a driver and inspector who stress their 
renewed effort to ensure people pay their fares. One worker 
reports having made 200 extra pesos in two weeks, and another 70 
pesos in four days. Maso interviews several customers who highly 
praise the renewed quality and timeliness of the service. Maso 
stresses that since December, when it was first implemented, 
absenteeism has dropped, the number of trips has increased, 
breakdowns have been eliminated, costs have been reduced, less 
fuel is being used, the workers' morale is higher, and the 
people are receiving better service. Maso concludes: "This is an 
experience worth imitating." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

