<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   UJC Leader Denies Generational Rift </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2201021194 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2201021194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Juan Contino, first secretary of the Union of Young 
Communists [UJC], today denied that there exists in our country 
a generational struggle for political power. Contino, the 
top-ranking UJC leader and also a member of the Central 
Committee of the Communist Party of Cuba, told PRENSA LATINA in 
an interview that people are in the habit of talking about a new 
generation's taking over from the old and that the term is 
inappropriate, because it is like saying: You have come this 
far; now only I will go forward, alone. 
  Contino stressed: There are three generations of 
revolutionaries living in Cuba today, who, far from having a 
tradition of antagonisms, are in full agreement regarding the 
principles, paths, and objectives of the revolutionary process 
begun in 1959. 
  The youth leader also denied that Cuban society is currently 
facing a values crisis. He did admit, however, that there are 
segments of the youthful population with whom Cuba is having 
difficulties because of the national economic situation. 

</TEXT>

