<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Ambassador Sees More Sanctions Ahead </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1901205294 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1901205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The threat of severe sanctions against Haiti are 
confirmed. Haitian Ambassador to the United Nations Fritz 
Longchamp confirmed on 18 January that the international 
community is considering increasing the sanctions. This 
decision was made after the failure of the talks with the 
military for relaunching the application of the Governors Island 
accord. Rothschild Francois, Junior reports: 
  [Begin Francois recording] We are perhaps moving toward the 
reinforcement of the sanctions against Haiti, most likely this 
week. Haitian UN Ambassador Fritz Longchamp has this information 
to us here in Miami. Fritz Longchamp was not able to specify 
for us the nature of those sanctions. However some UN sources, 
which prefer to remain anonymous, indicate that an air embargo 
could be ordered against Haiti. Other UN sources indicate that 
nothing has yet been decided on the question. A meeting of the 
Security Council should be held this week, as the 15 January 
deadline for the Haitian military to apply the Governor Island 
accord has passed. [passage omitted]. 
  It should be pointed out that President-in-exile 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide is due to travel to Canada on 23 January. 
On 24 January, he is due to meet with the new head of the 
Canadian government, Mr. Jean Chretien. 
  This has been Rothschild Francois, Junior, in Miami for 
Radio 
Metropole. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

