<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Factions' Reaction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2101000394 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2150 GMT 19 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2101000394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 19 Jan (NOTIMEX) -- The reforms to the 
Constitution approved by the Ecuadoran Congress have provoked 
various reactions among domestic political factions. 
  Legislators from the rightist Social Christian Party (which 
holds a majority in Congress), other progovernment parties, and 
independent parties voiced satisfaction over the reforms, which 
they described as "very important and justified." During a 
special session of Congress last night, a group of legislators 
promoted the constitutional reforms that will become effective 
in 1996. 
  Congress approved increasing the number of deputies (from 77 
to 113), the participation of independent candidates (except for 
the posts of president and vice president of the Republic), and 
the elimination of mid-term elections. The next step is to turn 
over the reforms to President Sixto Duran-Ballen for final 
approval. 
  Fernando Rosero, leader of the Ecuadoran Roldosist Party, 
announced his parliamentary faction will strive to abolish the 
reforms because they are the product of a "spurious" session. 
Deputies from minority parties -- the Democratic Left (ID), 
Popular Democracy Party, and Democratic People's Movement -- 
voiced their opposition and agreed that the approval of the 
reforms "showed some serious irregularities." 
  ID Deputy Antonio Rodriguez said increasing the number of 
deputies would imply a heavy allotment from the state budget. 
He added that President Duran-Ballen's ruling will allow 
knowing if his policy of reducing the state and exercising 
fiscal austerity is authentic. Minority deputies noted that the 
reforms had been approved in a very hasty manner, adding that 
these reforms were useful for "certain smug attitudes of the 
Social Christians." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

