<H3> <TI>   Congressional Blocs Disagree </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2201021794 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 20 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2201021794 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The constitutional reforms issue has promped a 
dispute between different congressional factions. Members of 
the opposition charge the issue of extending the deputies' term 
prompted a delay in the adjournment of the congressional 
sessions, but independent deputies claim the one has nothing to 
do with the other. 
  [Begin unidentified independent deputy recording] The 
adjournment of the congressional sessions, or a continuation of 
the sessions during a special period, have absolutely nothing to 
do with an extension of the deputies' term or their immediate 
re-election. We were emphatic about this, and those of us who 
participated in a political dialogue between Social Christians, 
conservatives, and independents said we will never discuss a 
transition period that may extend current deputies' term or lead 
to their immediate re-election --nothing that might benefit 
current individual deputies will be approved. [end recording] 
  The new majority seems to have scattered and constitutional 
reforms have been abolished for the time being. If the special 
period of sessions ends without discussing the reforms, they 
will be discussed on another occasion, starting from the 
beginning. 

</TEXT>

