<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation To Visit Vietnam To Enhance Economic Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1901232294 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
19 Jan 94 p B10 </F>

<F P=103> PY1901232294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by correspondent Reali Junior] </F>
  [Text] Paris -- A Brazilian economic delegation, made up of 
private businessmen and representatives from state-run 
companies, including Petrobras [Brazilian Petroleum 
Corporation], and headed by diplomat Celso Marques Vieira de 
Souza from the Foreign Ministry's Economic Promotion Department, 
is scheduled to visit Hanoi in late March to study the 
possibility of enhancing economic cooperation with Vietnam. 
  Brazil might reopen its embassy in Vietnam sometime this 
year, facilitating enhanced ties with Hanoi. The diplomats who 
will be participating in the trade delegation might discuss this 
issue with the Vietnamese. The Brazilian ambassador to 
Singapore is also the concurrent Brazilian ambassador to Vietnam. 
  Among the Asian countries, Vietnam is much in demand by 
European businessmen. The tourism industry, in addition to 
other forms of cooperation, has been developing significantly 
over the past two years. Hanoi authorities seem to be 
determined to follow the Chinese path of "market socialism," 
with an economic opening but keeping a closed political system. 
  In Vietnam there is a growth rate of 5 to 7 percent per year 
and an inflation rate of 5 percent per year. There are 72 
million inhabitants, of whom 40 percent are under 15 years of 
age. Labor costs, which are still very economical, range 
between $30 and $40 per month. Foreign capital is slowly 
returning to Vietnam. Efforts are also being made to integrate 
the country into international financial organizations. Vietnam 
is scheduled to receive an average of $2 billion per year in 
foreign investments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

