<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Council Demands Explanation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2301025094 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0159 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2301025094 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jesus Garzon for the "TV Today" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Just when the government thought the scandal over 
the U.S. forces' presence in Juanchaco had ended, the State 
Council exercised its constitutional authority and unanimously 
demanded an explanation from President Cesar Gaviria concerning 
the Marines' presence. The State Council president said Gaviria 
did not violate the Constitution if he had the Senate's 
approval; otherwise, he is in a serious situation. 
  President Gaviria has until 8 February to tell the State 
Council the truth about the U.S. forces' presence in Colombia 
and the overflights of U.S. aircraft on the country's northern 
coast. The 26 magistrates will then meet to study the situation 
and decide whether the Colombian president violated the 
Constitution. 
  For the time being, it is known that neither the Senate nor 
the State Council have been consulted by the government to allow 
the transit of U.S. soldiers through Colombian territory. 
  [Begin recording] [State Council President Amado Gutierrez] 
If the Senate has given its authorization, then he would 
obviously have no problem. 
  [Garzon] The Senate said no. 
  [Gutierrez] That is what we have to establish. [end 
recording] 
  According to the State Council, this is the first time a 
Colombian president has been questioned in connection with the 
presence of foreign troops in our country without prior approval 
from the Senate. 
  [Begin Gutierrez recording] There is no precedent for a 
State Council's ruling to allow the transit of foreign troops in 
the country. [end recording] 
  Therefore, in order to decide President Gaviria's 
culpability 
or innocence, the State Council expects to learn from the 
government under what conditions the permit was issued.[end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

