<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chile `Not Worried' Over Argentine Military Plane Purchase </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2401200894 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1518 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2401200894 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 24 Jan (NA) -- Upon arriving here on 
an official visit, Chilean Defense Minister Patricio Rojas said 
this morning that his country "is not worried" about the 
purchase of airplanes or any other type of materiel by the 
Argentine Armed Forces. 
  Rojas was met by Argentine Defense Minister Oscar Camilion; 
Lieutenant General Mario Candido Diaz, the joint staff chief; 
and other Defense Ministry officials and military leaders. 
  The Chilean minister will remain here just a few hours, as 
he 
is scheduled to return to Santiago this afternoon after meeting 
with Camilion and lunching at the Alvear Palace Hotel. 
  In remarks to the journalists, the two defense ministers 
ruled out the possibility of discussing the Laguna del Desierto 
border problem. 
  For his part, Camilion said the purchase of the A-4 Skyhawk 
planes will be decided during the meetings that Foreign Minister 
Guido Di Tella will hold with U.S. officials in the United 
States. 
  Camilion also confirmed a donation by the United States of 
three Hercules C-130 planes that will possibly arrive in 
Argentina before the end of the month. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51691 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat016_k_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
