<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Neuquen, Rio Negro Provinces Join Fiscal Pact </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2401224294 Buenos Aires LA PRENSA in Spanish 22 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PY2401224294 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA PRENSA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Carlos Menem obtained yesterday a clear 
political victory by getting the provinces of Neuquen and Rio 
Negro to join the fiscal pact. 
  After two days of negotiations in the Chapadmalal tourist 
resort, the government was able to get practically all the 
provinces to join the economic and fiscal guidelines of the 
central power. 
  Eduardo Angeloz [Cordoba Province governor] thus remained 
the 
single "rebel" governor who has not yet signed the pact drawn up 
by Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo. But the legislature of 
Corrientes Province must also decide whether or not it will 
approve the signing of the pact by Ideler Tonelli, who was then 
the trustee of that province. 
  Intense negotiations were carried out by Domingo Cavallo, 
presidential General Secretary Eduardo Bauza, and Interior 
Minister Carlos Ruckauf to get Neuquen Governor Jorge Sobisch 
and Rio Negro Governor Horacio Massaccesi to sign the pact. 
  Bauza himself later denied that pressure was exerted on the 
two governors, saying that the agreement with Neuquen and Rio 
Negro "considers the interests of the nation and of each 
province." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

