<F P=100> Bermuda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Management, Technology Minister Resigns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2001213194 Bridgetown CANA in English 2004 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2001213194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Hamilton, Bermuda, 20 Jan, CANA -- Bermuda's 
management and technology minister, Michael Winfield, has 
resigned his recently created cabinet post, citing business and 
family obligations. 
  The move took cabinet ministers by surprise and left Premier 
Sir John Swan not only with a vacant cabinet post, but without a 
government leader in the Senate (upper house), where Senator 
Winfield had steered the government agenda since 1992. 
  But a cabinet shuffle is unlikely, political sources say. 
  Environment Minister Gerald Simons is the logical choice as 
government leader in the Senate, while Senator Grant Gibbons is 
a strong bet to join the cabinet, possibly as minister of 
technology, the sources report. 
  The management portfolio would either be assumed by the new 
minister or handed to an existing minister. 
  An announcement from the premier is expected within days. 
  While giving up his other posts, Senator Winfield 40, will 
keep the seat he has held in the upper house since 1987. 
  Having managed successful United Bermuda Party campaigns in 
1983, 1985 and 1989, he is also expected to remain one of Sir 
John's political advisers. 
  "It's one of the most difficult decisions I have ever made," 
Senator Winfield said of his resignation, which was discussed 
with the premier on Monday and submitted when cabinet met this 
week. [Passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

