<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Units Reinforce Security in Uraba </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2401212594 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2401212594 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Military units began traveling to Uraba today from 
various areas around the country to reinforce security in 
response to the massacre that took place there. The first unit 
left from Valledupar. 
  On orders from the Army Staff, 240 professional soldiers of 
the 35th Counterguerrilla Battalion traveled to the Uraba region 
this morning. All of the soldiers are young men between 20 and 
25 years of age who are experienced in fighting subversives. 
For a year the troops have covered the mountains of regions 
where the irregulars are most active. For the last six months 
the soldiers have fought between the mountains of the Sierra 
Nevada de Santa Marta and the Perija Hills against FARC 
[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia] and ELN [Army of 
National Liberation] guerrillas, who continuously intimidate the 
citizens and cattle ranchers of Cesar Department. 
  [Begin German Guillermo Perico, commander of the 35th 
Counterguerrilla Battalion, recording; identified by caption] 
We will support military operations in the rural area and do 
our part to attain the peace that Colombia needs so much. [end 
recording] 
  The Army's strategy in the Uraba region is to increase the 
presence of the public force to exercise greater control in this 
conflict area. 
  Another counterguerrilla battalion could also be sent to 
that 
banana-producing region over the next few days. 
  This counterguerrilla mobile unit will fight the dissident 
group of the EPL [Popular Liberation Army] and the FARC, who are 
responsible for killings in the rural areas of the Uraba region 
in Antioquia Department. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

