<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mexicans Support U.S.-Chilean Free Trade Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2501013194 Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network in Spanish 
2200 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2501013194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Manola Robles] </F>
  [Excerpt] Speaking at the end of a meeting that a group of 
Mexican legislators held with President Patricio Aylwin, Mexican 
Senator Carlos Seles Gutierrez said the Mexican Senate and 
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari support the admission of 
Chile into a free trade agreement with the United States. 
  Speaking about the possibility of a free trade agreement 
with 
the United States, Seles said: 
  [Begin Seles recording, in progress] ...whether through 
NAFTA 
or a bilateral agreement. This depends on Chilean national 
interests. Overall we held a cordial meeting, during which we 
discussed the progress that our bilateral ties have experienced. 
[end recording] 
  Commenting on persistent oppostion to NAFTA in Mexico, Seles 
said that any U.S.-Chilean free trade agreement would be based 
on very different terms than those of the U.S.-Mexican 
agreement, because 70 percent of Mexican trade is targeted at 
the United States. 
  [Begin Seles Recording] I do not believe we will experience 
the great impact that people are talking about, because if labor 
costs were the determinant factor for companies establishing 
themselves, then they would be establishing themselves in Haiti 
or in countries that pay lower salaries than ours. 
  I believe the NAFTA agreement will inevitably lead to new 
investments in Mexico. However, we Mexicans believe we will be 
luring greater investment from countries oustide NAFTA, that is, 
outside the United States and Canada. We believe we will be 
luring greater investment from Asian and Pacific Rim countries, 
mainly from Japan, and from Europe, which together with Mexicans 
will be able to exploit Mexican resources to reach the huge 
American market. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

