<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Utility Rates To Be Corrected Below Inflation Rate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2501115694 Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network in 
Portuguese 0900 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2501115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The finance, planning, and mines and energy 
ministers yesterday announced -- two days ahead -- that fuel 
prices would be increased by 16.5-percent as of 26 January. 
  The peculiarity in this increase is that the price 
adjustment 
is lower than the inflation rate. 
  The fuel price adjustment for January will stand at 36.3 
percent, compared with 38.6 percent in December. This means the 
adjustment is 2.3-percent less. The drop is based on a cut in 
international oil prices and an increase in the productivity of 
Petrobras [Brazilian Petroleum Corporation]. 
  This increase will have a 0.7-percent impact on the 
wholesale 
price index calculated by the Getulio Vargas Foundation. 
  Winston Fritsch, Finance Ministry economic policy secretary, 
said that the policy of correcting prices below the inflation 
rate will be extended to all the utility rates. 

</TEXT>

