<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Denies More Flights to U.S. Airline </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1901012994 Buenos Aires LA NACION in Spanish 16 Jan 94 
Section 1, p 14--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1901012994 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA NACION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Economy Ministry sources disclosed that the 
government has not authorized the U.S. company American Airlines 
to increase the frequency of its flights to and from Argentina 
during the low season. 
  This refusal follows a similar one issued in November 
against 
a similar petition filed by American Airlines and United 
Airlines and supported by U.S. Ambassador James Cheek. 
  American Airlines was informed of the refusal while the 
economic team was holding meetings with Iberia officials to 
negotiate the possibility of increasing Argentine Airlines' 
capital. 
  An Economy Ministry official explained that the official 
refusal of American Airlines' proposal was prompted by Argentine 
Airlines' commitment to cover all the demand, which, according 
to the U.S. company, exceeds 60 percent of the available seats. 
  This gesture indicates that the government is issuing 
favorable signals to Argentine Airlines' operator. 
  The economic negotiation did not manage to find a solution 
to 
Iberia's petition to increase Argentine Airlines' capital. An 
official source said: "If it is not demonstrated that the 
company is economically viable, it is useless to make any 
capital contributions." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

