<F P=101> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demonstrators Protest Presence of U.S. Military Personnel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2201191394 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1703 GMT 22 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2201191394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 22 Jan (PL) -- Hundreds of 
demonstrators in the Colombian cities of Medellin and Santa Fe 
de Bogota burned U.S. flags to protest the presence of U.S. 
military personnel in this country, local media reported today. 
  In Medellin, capital of Antioquia Department, northwest of 
here, and Santa Fe de Bogota these actions occurred for the 
second time in a little less than one week, carried out by 
members of student and youth organizations, the sources added. 
  The first contingent of U.S. military troops arrived on the 
Colombian Pacific Coast late in December with the announced 
purpose of building a school and hospital in that region. 
  There are currently some 259 U.S. troops, who must leave 
Colombia in three months, although journalistic circles speak of 
a possible extension of their stay. 

</TEXT>

