<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina Denies Willingness to Send Troops to Angola </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2101002594 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2216 GMT 20 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2101002594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by special reporter Eduardo Rodriguez-Baz] </F>
  [Text] Windhoek, 20 Jan (PL) -- Today, Cuban Foreign 
Minister Roberto Robaina denied media reports noting that his 
country would send troops to Angola if it detects foreign 
intervention there. In exclusive statements to PRENSA LATINA, 
Robaina described these reports as clumsy, ill-intended 
maneuvers. 
  Cuba fully respects the negotiations that are under way 
between the Angolan Government and National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola in Lusaka, Zambia, in the search for a 
peaceful solution to the Angolan conflict, Robaina emphasized. 
  The Cuban delegation is very much aware of the absurd nature 
of this maneuver. The issue was discussed from the beginning, 
and our position of nonintervention was clearly established. Our 
stand, however, is being distorted precisely at the place where 
the talks are being held. 
  The foreign minister noted the fact that the topic was 
discussed with the Angolans themselves, and the fact that Havana 
clearly established its position of nonintervention in their 
internal affairs should attract the attention of many people. 
  Cuba maintains full respect for the inter-Angolan dialogue 
and this position was even stated to President Jose Eduardo Dos 
Santos, he concluded. 
  Robaina began a two-week tour that included Ghana, Angola, 
Zimbabwe, Zambia, and Namibia on 9 January. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

