<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Signs Trade Agreement in Namibia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2101232994 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0951 GMT 21 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2101232994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Windhoek, 21 Jan (PL) -- The Cuban and Namibian 
Governments signed today in this capital an important commercial 
agreement granting each other most favored nation status. 
  The document, which will be valid for three years, was 
signed 
by Cuban Foreign Relations Minister Roberto Robaina and Hidipo 
Hamutenya, Namibian trade and industry minister. 
  According to the agreement, the contracting parties will 
make 
all payments in freely convertible currency and in accordance 
with the laws of both states. 
  However, the signatories may adopt other forms of payment to 
promote the rapid development of commercial ties, the document 
said. 
  Robaina and Hamutenya agreed that this bilateral accord will 
create new ways to identify other areas of cooperation. 
  The Havana and Windhoek Foreign Ministries last Wednesday 
signed another agreement to eliminate visa requirements for the 
citizens of both nations. 
  Robaina today concludes a three-day visit to Namibia, the 
last leg of a two-week tour of Africa, which also took him to 
Ghana, Angola, Zimbabwe, and Zambia. 
  Before leaving for his country, the Cuban foreign relations 
minister will speak to Namibian President Sam Nujoma, to whom he 
will present a message from President Fidel Castro. 

</TEXT>

