<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Medellin Demonstrators Burn U.S. Flag To Protest Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1901194094 Santa Fe de Bogota EL NUEVO SIGLO in Spanish 16 
Jan 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PA1901194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL NUEVO SIGLO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A group of enraged citizens in Antioquia Department 
on 15 January burned a U.S. flag in the center of Medellin to 
protest the presence of U.S. troops in Juanchaco and the eastern 
plains. 
  The protest began early in the evening when a group of at 
least 70 people went to the Colombian-American Cultural 
Institute in Medellin, chanted slogans against the Colombian and 
U.S. Governments, and burned the U.S. flag. 
  The demonstrators demanded the expulsion of U.S. soldiers 
from Colombia, considering their presence an invasion. 
  They also demanded that President Cesar Gaviria enforce 
respect for national sovereignty and that he explain the real 
reasons why a group of U.S. soldiers with sophisticated 
equipment and machinery is in Juanchaco, on the Pacific coast, 
and the eastern plains. 
  Authorities reported that after the U.S. flag was burned, 
the 
demonstration, which lasted 15 minutes, quickly broke up without 
any need for intervention by the police. 

</TEXT>

