<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Young Communists Seek New Contacts Abroad </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2201035594 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1821 GMT 20 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2201035594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Reprot by Zenaida Ferrer Martinez] </F>
  [Text] Havana, 20 Jan (PL) -- The Union of Young Communists 
(UJC) has increased its contacts with youth organizations and 
institutions around the world in recent years, currently 
maintaining relations with 218 entities in 61 countries. 
  In an exclusive interview with PRENSA LATINA, Juan Contino, 
the first secretary of the national UJC said there are new paths 
toward knowledge opening up for the world's younger generations, 
especially young people in Latin America, the Caribbean, Europe, 
and the socialist countries (China, Vietnam, and North Korea). 
  The youth leader welcomed the international demonstrations 
of 
solidarity and support received from all corners of the world, 
particularly those from people speaking out against the U.S. 
blockade of the island at public forums, even within the United 
States itself. 
  He said that many young friends of Cuba are launching an 
offensive to disseminate information all over the world 
regarding the democratic system on the island and its respect 
for human rights in an effort to counter the smear campaigns 
promoted by the enemies of the revolution. 
  He noted there has been a recent increase in examples of 
solidarity toward the Caribbean country's people in the form of 
events, demonstrations, and other means of dissemination, as 
well as in the form of assorted donations, particularly to 
contribute to the education effort. 
  Contino, who is also a member of the Central Committee, 
highlighted the fact that 334 youngsters belonging to 15 
international labor brigades visited the island in 1993. These 
individuals paid their own way and worked in the fields at the 
Paraiso Youth Camp in Havana Province, just outside this capital 
city. 
  Contino said activities similar to those carried out on the 
island to commemorate and support the Cuban sociopolitical 
system are currently being organized in 15 nations on the 
occasion of the 35th anniversary of the triumph of the 
revolution headed by Fidel Castro. These activities have been 
blessed "by Cuba forever." 
  He said that groups of youth leaders are going to various 
parts of the world and will participate in festivities in 
countries such as Colombia, Mexico, Brazil, Spain, France, 
Italy, Portugal, and Vietnam, among others. 
  The 33-year-old economist, who has seven years of experience 
as a youth leader, expressed his gratitude to youth and student 
organizations, associations, and entities from throughout the 
world for making it possible for the UJC to expand its contacts 
and exchange programs abroad during the current difficult 
situation. 
  Contino said the 550,000 UJC militants who represent Cuba's 
3.1 million young people are making efforts to deserve the 
esteem of friends from other countries and are giving foremost 
attention to their work in the edification of the Cuban 
socialist system. 
  The UJC is a selective organization that embodies the 
vanguard of the Cuban youth sector and has affiliates in all 
sectors of the island's social and economic life. The roots of 
this organization are in the country's secondary schools and 
universities. 
  The UJC was founded on 4 April 1961. Hundreds of thousands 
of Cubans have been members of it -- in particular, many current 
leaders of the Communist Party of Cuba. According to Contino, 
the UJC views itself as the party's best quarry for talent -- 
one that shapes people who continue the tradition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

