<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   EXPRESO: Watson's Attitude `Paternalistic' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2401141794 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2140 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2401141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 23 Jan (EFE) -- The attitude of Alexander 
Watson -- U.S. under secretary of state for Inter-American 
Affairs -- during his recent visit to Peru was considered 
paternalistic in an editorial published today by EXPRESO, a Lima 
daily. 
  In a critical tone, the editorial noted that the U.S. high- 
ranking government official who was in Lima this week on a 
three-day official visit "came and took notes -- as if he had a 
superior right -- as to whether we have `progressed' in 
democracy, justice administration, and human rights." 
  The daily considers that Watson gave the impression of 
encouraging those who object to "the very existence of 
(President Alberto Fujimori's) government and the new 
Constitution," making reference to the meeting the under 
secretary of state held with opposition political sectors. 
  "It is not a way to create a climate of democratic consensus 
that will close the gap opened on 5 April. It is not enough to 
call for a dialogue," EXPRESO comments in reference to the 5 
April 1992 coup staged by Fujimori in which he dissolved 
Congress and stripped the Judicial Branch, while he assumed 
total power. 
  EXPRESO -- which supports the government -- adds that Watson 
admitted that in Peru progress had been made with respect to 
human rights and democracy. Nevertheless, he had said "there is 
still much more to do." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

