<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Breaks Off Talks With Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2401232794 Managua Radio Corporacion in Spanish 2200 GMT 
24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2401232794 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Corporacion </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Five O'Clock Sharp" newscast] </F>
  [Text] We have last-minute information on the negotiations 
between leaders of the transportation sector and the government. 
[four-second break in transmission] We repeat: The 
negotiations between the transportation workers and government 
have been broken off. We receive this last-minute report from 
Carlos Torres, chief editor of the "Five O'Clock Sharp" 
newscast. Carlos Torres, tell us what has happened. 
  [Torres] The negotiations between the government and the 
transportation sector were broken off a few hours ago. The 
members of the National Transportation Commission withdrew, 
because they are demanding the government conduct the 
negotiations only with the National Transportation Commission. 
  Labor Minister Francisco Rosales expressed regret over the 
withdrawal of the National Transportation Commission members and 
said the government had called the entire National 
Transportation Council to study the agreements. The Nicaraguan 
Transportation Chamber president reported that three members of 
the Transportation Chamber were attacked in the Metro Centro 
sector this morning and directly accused Roberto Gonzalez, the 
main leader of the Parrales Vallejos [bus cooperative] of being 
involved in this event. Gonzalez denied his accusations, however. 
  Francisco Rosales and Emilio Pereira, the labor and finance 
ministers respectively, have just gone to the second floor of 
the National Assembly to talk to Assembly President Luis 
Humberto Guzman to try to find a solution to the transportation 
problem. Roberto Gonzalez and members of the National 
Transportation Commission have said their demands will be 
tougher tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

