<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Secretary To Chair </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2401233994 Mexico City Canal 13 Azteca Network in Spanish 
1300 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2401233994 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Azteca Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Good Morning From Mexico" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Carlos Salinas de Gortari this weekend 
appointed the Amnesty and Reconciliation Commission in Chiapas 
in accordance with the Amnesty Law approved by the legislative 
branch. 
  During the meeting in which the commission was established, 
President Salinas urged the commissioners to immediately begin 
assuming their responsibilities as outlined in the Amnesty Law, 
which has been in force since Saturday. This commission will 
watch over the full implementation of the guarantees established 
in the Amnesty Law for those who turn over their weapons. These 
people cannot be questioned or detained. Likewise, the 
commission will speed up the legal proceedings, and it will be 
responsible for declaring the official end of the Chiapas 
conflict. 
  The Amnesty Commission comprises the following 
representives: 
the government secretary, who chairs the commission; the 
secretary of social development; the prosecutor general of the 
Republic; the agrarian prosecutor general; the director of the 
National Indian Institute; and the director of the Overall 
Development and Social Justice Commission for the Indian people. 
Jose Narro Robles was appointed technical secretary of the 
Amnesty Commission. 

</TEXT>

