<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace Commissioner: Peace Process at Standstill </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2401212794 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2401212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Samuel Prieto from the "Good Morning From Mexico" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] This weekend, Manuel Camacho Solis, commissioner for 
peace and reconciliation in Chiapas, admitted he perceives signs 
of exhaustion in his dialogue strategy with the rebel group, 
which have brought the peace process to a standstill. This 
problem, Camacho said, is reflected in three worrisome issues, 
whose adequate solution depends on continued confidence in the 
strategy and in renewed progress. 
  The first issue, he said, involves serious concerns about 
the 
proceedings implemented through the Amnesty Law for the purpose 
of making it increasingly restrictive. Camacho went on to 
explain that this is the key issue among many difficult factors 
in the conflict, and if it is not resolved it may lead to the 
loss of a great opportunity for amnesty and the return of the 
EZLN [Zapatist Army of National Liberation] nonmilitant members 
to their communities in a reprisal-free climate. 
  The second issue is a question: What is the agenda and, 
especially, how can national issues be resolved and the 
Republic's institutions strengthened without upsetting the legal 
order? Concerning this issue, Camacho Solis pointed out that 
amnesty contains guarantees for the state and society and, 
therefore, the cessation of hostilities is a condition for its 
concession. The requirements for the implementation of amnesty, 
however, must be imaginatively and actively fulfilled. 
  Regarding their agendas, which the fulfillment of the 
consolidation of the peace process depends on, Camacho said the 
regional agenda will, by and large, redefine the relationship 
between the Chiapas communities and the institutions. Changes 
must be made, even in public priorities, to devote more 
attention to the Indian regions. Meanwhile, the national agenda 
cannot associate the possibility of change within the country 
with the dynamics of an armed movement if there is to be a 
democratic government. 
  The third issue, Camacho stressed, is that demands have been 
made of him to explain the connection between his activities and 
politics. In this regard, he pointed out it is essential to 
achieve a political solution to this conflict to ensure a 
favorable climate for 1994. Everyone, he insisted, must execute 
the policies entrusted to him. Camacho said he will be 
completely devoted to this task as long as he can be useful. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51792 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat016_c_94005" </HT>


