<H3> <TI>   Chamber President Questions Sanctions' Double Standard </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2401230194 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in Creole 1230 
GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2401230194 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Creole </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Chamber of Deputies President Frantz Robert Monde 
does not agree that the international community should increase 
sanctions against the country. According to Deputy Monde, the 
sanctions have never done anything positive for the country's 
crisis, have only made the rich richer, and the poor poorer. 
Monde asks the international community to revise its behavior in 
the Haitian crisis. 
  [Begin recording, in French] I think the international 
community has gotten off to a bad start with... [changes 
thought] Given the stand it has taken, the international 
community has not played the role of arbitrator. It must 
readjust its fire: Adopting further measures against Haiti would 
be a grave error, not to mention an aberration, because -- let 
us be honest -- the agreement was violated by the Army, it says. 
Let us accept that as a fait accompli. But Aristide also 
violated the Washington agreement even at the United Nations 
tribunal. No sanctions were imposed against Aristide. Why are 
there two sets of standards? [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

