<F P=100> Bermuda </F>
<F P=101> St. Vincent and the Grenadines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Parties Form Alliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2401181694 Bridgetown CANA in English 1620 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2401181694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kingstown, St. Vincent, 24 Jan, CANA -- The St. 
Vincent and the Grenadines Labour Party (SVLP) and the Movement 
for National Unity (MNU) have formed an alliance to contest the 
February 21 general election in which the ruling New Democratic 
Party (NDP) will be seeking a third straight term. 
  A joint announcement by the leaders of both parties - 
Stanley 
John of the SVLP and Dr Ralph Gonsalves of the MNU - said 
Vincent Beache, a former trade minister and SVLP leader, was 
chosen to lead the alliance. 
  The alliance will contest the 15 seats in the House of 
Assembly with the SVLP providing nine candidates and the MNU, 
six. In the just dissolved Parliament, neither party was 
represented. 
  Despite formation of the alliance, the two parties will 
retain their identities "but will present a common manifesto and 
share a common campaign platform," the statement said. 
  "This agreement was facilitated by the "Concerned Citizens 
Committee", a group of prominent Vincentian business persons, 
professionals and members of clergy who have recently come 
together to ensure good governance in the state," the statement 
added. 
  John will continue to function as leader of the SVLP and 
Gonsalves as head of the MNU. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

