<F P=100> Bermuda </F>
<F P=101> St. Kitts and Nevis </F>
<H3> <TI>   PM Simmonds Appeals for Election Law and Order </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601014994 Bridgetown CANA in English 2112 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2601014994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Basseterre, St. Kitts, 25 Jan, CANA -- St. Kitts and 
Nevis prime minister, Dr. Kennedy Simmonds, has appealed for the 
maintenance of law and order as opposition politicians prepare 
to step up their campaign for fresh general elections. Simmonds 
made the appeal ahead of Wednesday's start of a new session of 
parliament. 
  Simmonds went on ZIZ, the state-owned radio and television 
system, Monday night to urge restraint in the face of a planned 
protest demonstration by the St. Kitts-Nevis Labour Party 
(SKNLP). Simmonds said his opponents should pursue the 
parliamentary process and the courts to settle their grievances. 
  The Labour Party, like Simmonds' People's Action Movement 
(PAM), captured four seats in the November 29 poll but a larger 
majority of the popular vote. PAM teamed up with the Nevis 
Reformation Party to form a minority government. The Labour 
Party has been canvassing support across St. Kitts for a show of 
strength on Wednesday. The successful SKNLP candidates say they 
will not be taking up their seats in parliament, but would 
instead protest the swearing in of the minority government. 
  The installation of the government led to clashes between 
the 
police and Labour Party supporters on December 2. Prime Minister 
Simmonds said the police had given no permission for a 
demonstration on Wednesday and warned: "Those who break the law 
will be dealt with appropriately." 
  Referring to the December disturbance, which hurt the 
tourist 
industry, Simmonds said: "...We cannot afford or tolerate any 
similar disturbances now or in the future. We saw how quickly 
our country was set back and how abruptly the cruise ship trade 
dried up. Our economy is strong now and we need to keep it that 
way, but it can only remain so by the maintenance of law and 
order. But the Labour Party has threatened to close down town. 
  Dr. Assim Martin, one of Labour's successful candidates, 
said 
the price for freedom and democracy was high "and we are 
prepared to make the ultimate sacrifice, not just for ourselves, 
but for all the people. We are prepared and ready, just like the 
people of South Africa who will get the choice of majority rule 
in April," said Martin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

