<F P=100> Bermuda </F>
<F P=101> St. Vincent and the Grenadines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Historian Predicts Mitchell Reelection </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601031794 Bridgetown CANA in English 2136 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2601031794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kingstown, St. Vincent, 25 Jan, CANA -- An 
opposition alliance to fight a February 21 general election in 
St. Vincent and the Grenadines will have to do some hard 
campaigning to win favour with the electorate, according to 
historian, Dr. Adrian Fraser. Fraser said the new group will 
have to sell itself hard to the electorate, since Prime Minister 
James Mitchell's New Democratic Party would exploit some of the 
questions about itself that the alliance has not answered. 
  He told CANA the alliance "raises more questions than it 
provides answers because one hopes that it has come about 
because of dissatisfaction with the state of things." He asked: 
"Have they been looking beyond the election?" 
  On Monday, the St. Vincent and the Grenadines Labour Party, 
led by lawyer Stanley John, and Dr. Ralph Gonsalves' Movement 
for National Unity announced that they had formed an alliance. 
The two parties will campaign on a common platform and share a 
single manifesto, but retain their individual identities. 
  Prime Minister Mitchell, whose party won all fifteen seats 
in the last general election, remains confident about a third 
straight win. He told CANA: "No last-minute strategy of an 
alliance of convenience by the opposition parties can prevent us 
from securing a third consecutive mandate from the people of St. 
Vincent and the Grenadines." 

</TEXT>

