<H3> <TI>   Transportation Strike Continues; More Talks Scheduled </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2501235894 Managua Radio Catolica in Spanish 2200 GMT 25 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2501235894 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Catolica </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report from the National Assembly in Managua </F>
on talks between representatives of the transportation industry 
and the government; from the "The Nation Radio Newspaper"] 
  [Excerpt] This afternoon, the National Transport Commission 
failed to attend negotiations that the government opened with 
the four organizations that make up the National Transportation 
Council. The two transportation chambers and the two 
transportation federations -- Fetracanic [Federation of 
Nicaraguan Cargo Carriers] and Fetracolnic [Federation of 
Nicaraguan of Passenger Carriers] -- are holding a meeting on 
the second floor of the Presidency in an effort to reach 
agreements to put an end to the problems caused by this strike. 
Journalists outside the Presidency have been denied access to 
the meeting on instructions from the Presidency's Public 
Relations Office. The journalists, however, are waiting for 
results of the talks. 
  Nevertheless, the strike will not be resolved, at least 
today, because of the National Transportation Commission's 
absence. The vehicles that had been blocking the nearby streets 
were removed this afternoon. Talks are expected to be resumed 
tomorrow. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

